## What’s happening here:

* #### HTML layer → added a <button> with onclick="makeDogBark()".

* #### CSS layer → styled the button so it looks nice.

* #### JavaScript layer → function makeDogBark() shows an alert popup saying "Woof! Woof! 🐶".


## In other words:
* #### HTML = button exists

* #### CSS = button looks good

* #### JavaScript = button does something


<div style="text-align: left;">
    <img src="https://images.code.org/8347eb9717a55b91277116cceea55d10-image-1759505960693.png" 
         alt="<button> → Creates a clickable button on the page.
onclick=makeDogBark() → Tells the button to run the makeDogBark function when clicked.
<script> ... </script> → The place inside your HTML where you can write JavaScript code.
function makeDogBark() { ... } → Defines a reusable block of code that runs when called.
alert(Woof! Woof! 🐶); → Pops up a message box that says Woof! Woof! 🐶 when the function is triggered."
